            <div class=3D"container discover-tips-content-wrapper">

            <div class=3D"discover-title-container frames-measurement-conta=
iner">
                <div class=3D"discover-title clearfix">
                    <h1>Glasses Measurements &amp; Frame sizes</h1>
                </div>
                <div class=3D"discover-reviewd">Reviewed by : <a href=3D"ht=
tps://www.eyebuydirect.com/eyecare/our-vision-experts/matthew-miller" class=
=3D"author"> Dr. Matthew Miller, OD</a> on May 19th, 2022</div>
                <p>Finding the right frame size is an important part of buy=
ing eyewear online. Luckily, it's also super simple! Below is a helpful gui=
de to understanding glasses measurements and sizes when looking for your ne=
xt pair of eyeglasses or sunglasses.</p>
            </div>
            <div class=3D"read-frame-size">
                <div class=3D"frame-size-content">
                    <p class=3D"size-content-one">To ensure your frames fit=
 correctly, you must first determine what frame size is best for you. The b=
est place to start is by taking the measurements of a pair that you already=
 wear and feel comfortable in.</p>
                    <p>You can usually find the measurements on the inside =
of the temple of your glasses. Some may also refer to this section as the "=
arm" of your glasses. The frame measurements normally appear as three numbe=
rs separated by dashes =E2=80=94 for example, 48-19-140. These three number=
s reflect the measurements of different parts of the frames.</p>
                </div>

                <div class=3D"frame-measurements-desc clearfix">
                    <div class=3D"frame-measurements-content clearfix">
                        <div class=3D"frame-size-img-container">
                            <div class=3D"frame-size-img">
                                <img class=3D" lazyloaded" src=3D"https://i=
mg.ebdcdn.com/image/upload/static/images/discover/tips/frame-measurements-s=
ize-new.jpg?q=3D85" data-src=3D"https://img.ebdcdn.com/image/upload/static/=
images/discover/tips/frame-measurements-size-new.jpg?q=3D85" alt=3D"glasses=
 frame sizes">
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class=3D"frame-measurements-order">
                            <p class=3D"following-order">From left to right=
, the numbers tell you the:</p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>1. Lens width</li>
                                <li>2. Bridge width</li>
                                <li>3. Temple length</li>
                            </ul>
                            <p class=3D"finish-order">Sometimes a fourth nu=
mber will be noted on the arm, and this is your lens height. Keep in mind t=
hat all these measurements are in millimeters.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class=3D"frame-size-details">
                    <ul>
                        <!-- Lens Width -->
                        <li class=3D"clearfix">
                            <div class=3D"size-details-img-container">
                                <div class=3D"size-details-img">
                                    <img class=3D" lazyloaded" src=3D"https=
://img.ebdcdn.com/image/upload/static/images/discover/tips/frame-measuremen=
ts-legend-01-01.jpg?q=3D85" data-src=3D"https://img.ebdcdn.com/image/upload=
/static/images/discover/tips/frame-measurements-legend-01-01.jpg?q=3D85" al=
t=3D"Lens Width">
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class=3D"size-details">
                                <h5><span class=3D"details-title">Lens Widt=
h</span><span class=3D"frame-measurements-im-01"></span></h5>
                                <p>This is the horizontal width of each len=
s, measured at its widest point.  Also called eye size, it typically ranges=
 from 40 mm to 60 mm.</p>
                            </div>
                        </li>
                        <!-- Bridge Width -->
                        <li class=3D"clearfix">
                            <div class=3D"size-details-img-container bridge=
-img-container">
                                <div class=3D"size-details-img">
                                    <img class=3D" lazyloaded" src=3D"https=
://img.ebdcdn.com/image/upload/static/images/discover/tips/frame-measuremen=
ts-legend-01-02.jpg?q=3D85" data-src=3D"https://img.ebdcdn.com/image/upload=
/static/images/discover/tips/frame-measurements-legend-01-02.jpg?q=3D85" al=
t=3D"Bridge Width">
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class=3D"size-details">
                                <h5><span class=3D"details-title">Bridge Wi=
dth</span><span class=3D"frame-measurements-im-02"></span></h5>
                                <p>This is the distance between your two le=
nses. In short, the bridge width is the space where your frames fit against=
 your nose. The bridge size ranges from 14 mm to 24 mm.</p>
                            </div>
                        </li>
                        <!-- Temple (Arm) Length -->
                        <li class=3D"clearfix">
                            <div class=3D"size-details-img-container temple=
-img-container">
                                <div class=3D"size-details-img">
                                    <img class=3D"lazyload" src=3D"data:ima=
ge/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw=3D=3D" dat=
a-src=3D"https://img.ebdcdn.com/image/upload/static/images/discover/tips/fr=
ame-measurements-legend-01-03.jpg?q=3D85" alt=3D"Temple Length">
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class=3D"size-details">
                                <h5><span class=3D"details-title">Temple (A=
rm) Length</span><span class=3D"frame-measurements-im-03"></span></h5>
                                <p>This is the length of the temple from th=
e hinge to the temple tip, including the bended part that sits on your ear.=
 The arm length is typically 120 mm to 150 mm long.</p>
                            </div>
                        </li>
                        <!-- Lens Height -->
                        <li class=3D"clearfix lens-height">
                            <div class=3D"size-details-img-container lens-i=
mg-container">
                                <div class=3D"size-details-img">
                                    <img class=3D"lazyload" src=3D"data:ima=
ge/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw=3D=3D" dat=
a-src=3D"https://img.ebdcdn.com/image/upload/static/images/discover/tips/fr=
ame-measurements-legend-01-04.jpg?q=3D85" alt=3D"Lens Height">
                                </div>
                            </div>
                            <div class=3D"size-details">
                                <h5><span class=3D"details-title">Lens Heig=
ht</span></h5>
                                <p>This is the vertical height of your lens=
es. The measurement for it is taken at the widest point of the lens within =
the frame. Lens height is especially important when measuring bifocal or pr=
ogressive lenses.</p>
                            </div>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <!-- A Few Helpful Tips For Eyeglass Measurements -->
                <div class=3D"helpful-tips-container">
                    <h2>A Few Helpful Tips for Glasses Measurements</h2>
                    <ul>
                        <!-- Finding the Perfect Frame Width -->
                        <li class=3D"helpful-tips-details">
                            <div class=3D"helpful-tips-title  tips-title cl=
earfix">
                                <div class=3D"empty-container">
                                    <div class=3D"img-container"></div>
                                </div>
                                <h5>Find the Perfect Frame Width</h5>
                                <i class=3D"icon-arrow-down"></i>
                            </div>
                            <div class=3D"helpful-tips-content clearfix">
                                <div class=3D"tips-img-container finding-im=
g-container">
                                    <div class=3D"img-container">
                                        <img class=3D"lazyload" src=3D"data=
:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw=3D=3D"=
 data-src=3D"https://img.ebdcdn.com/image/upload/static/images/discover/tip=
s/frame-measurements-legend-02.jpg?q=3D85" alt=3D"Frame Width">
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class=3D"helpful-tips-desc">
                                    <p class=3D"">A too-narrow frame will m=
ake your face look wider, while a frame that is too wide will make your fac=
e look narrower. This is one of the most important factors in finding a pai=
r of glasses that fits your face shape. Find a frame that is slightly wider=
 than your face =E2=80=94 no more than a finger width between the temple an=
d your face. Any wider than this is a sign your frames are too wide.</p>
                                    <div class=3D"light-icon-content">
                                        <div class=3D"light-icon-desc">
                                            <ins class=3D"im"></ins>
                                            <span>This measurement is not p=
rinted on the temple of your glasses. To find it, take your measuring tape =
and run it horizontally across the front of your frames. Be sure to include=
 any hinges or design features that stick out on the sides in the final mea=
surement.</span>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </li>
                        <!-- Get Cozy with Your Temple Length -->
                        <li class=3D"helpful-tips-details">
                            <div class=3D"helpful-tips-title clearfix">
                                <div class=3D"empty-container">
                                    <div class=3D"img-container"></div>
                                </div>
                                <h5>Understand Your Temple Length</h5>
                                <i class=3D"icon-arrow-down"></i>
                            </div>
                            <div class=3D"helpful-tips-content clearfix">
                                <div class=3D"tips-img-container get-img-co=
ntainer">
                                    <div class=3D"img-container">
                                        <img class=3D"lazyload" src=3D"data=
:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw=3D=3D"=
 data-src=3D"https://img.ebdcdn.com/image/upload/static/images/discover/tip=
s/frame-measurements-legend-03.jpg?q=3D85" alt=3D"Temple Length">
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class=3D"helpful-tips-desc">
                                    <p class=3D"">Temple length is the meas=
urement in millimeters of each =E2=80=9Carm=E2=80=9D of the frame. This mea=
surement does not vary as much as the others. The most common options are 1=
35 mm, 140 mm, 145 mm, and 150 mm. The temples should fit horizontally and =
evenly along the sides of your head, and fit comfortably along the outside =
of your ear.</p>
                                    <div class=3D"light-icon-content">
                                        <div class=3D"light-icon-desc">
                                            <ins class=3D"im"></ins>
                                            <span>To find your temple lengt=
h, measure from the hinge screws to the tip of the arm.</span>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </li>
                        <!-- Picking the Right Lens Height and Width -->
                        <li class=3D"helpful-tips-details">
                            <div class=3D"helpful-tips-title  tips-title cl=
earfix">
                                <div class=3D"empty-container">
                                    <div class=3D"img-container"></div>
                                </div>
                                <h5>Pick the Right Lens Height and Width</h=
5>
                                <i class=3D"icon-arrow-down"></i>
                            </div>
                            <div class=3D"helpful-tips-content clearfix">
                                <div class=3D"tips-img-container picking-im=
g-container">
                                    <div class=3D"other-img-container">
                                        <img class=3D"lazyload" src=3D"data=
:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw=3D=3D"=
 data-src=3D"https://img.ebdcdn.com/image/upload/static/images/discover/tip=
s/frame-measurements-legend-04.jpg?q=3D85" alt=3D"Height and Width">
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class=3D"helpful-tips-desc">
                                    <p class=3D"tips-desc-first">To determi=
ne which lens size is right for you, know that a small lens width is 50 mm =
or less, medium is between 51 mm and 54 mm, and large is any lens wider tha=
n 55 mm.</p>
                                    <p class=3D"tips-desc-second">Your eyes=
 should be centered within your lenses. Eyeglass frames that are too wide c=
an make your eyes appear too close together, while narrow frames will give =
your eyes a wide-set look.</p>
                                    <div class=3D"light-icon-content">
                                        <div class=3D"light-icon-desc picki=
ng-icon-desc">
                                            <ins class=3D"im"></ins>
                                            <span>To find the lens height a=
nd width, measure the widest and tallest parts of the lens.</span>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </li>
                        <!-- Selecting the Ideal Bridge Width -->
                        <li class=3D"helpful-tips-details">
                            <div class=3D"helpful-tips-title clearfix">
                                <div class=3D"empty-container">
                                    <div class=3D"img-container"></div>
                                </div>
                                <h5>Select the Ideal Bridge Width</h5>
                                <i class=3D"icon-arrow-down"></i>
                            </div>
                            <div class=3D"helpful-tips-content clearfix">
                                <div class=3D"tips-img-container selecting-=
img-container">
                                    <div class=3D"other-img-container">
                                        <img class=3D"lazyload" src=3D"data=
:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw=3D=3D"=
 data-src=3D"https://img.ebdcdn.com/image/upload/static/images/discover/tip=
s/frame-measurements-legend-05.jpg?q=3D85" alt=3D"Bridge Width">
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <div class=3D"helpful-tips-desc select-tips=
-desc">
                                    <p class=3D"tips-desc-first">The distan=
ce between a frame=E2=80=99s lenses is its bridge width. The bridge should =
sit comfortably on your nose. If you have close-set eyes or need a narrow b=
ridge, this number should be smaller. If you have wide-set eyes or want a w=
ide bridge, this number should be larger.</p>
                                    <p class=3D"tips-desc-second">The locat=
ion of your nose can help determine which frame style works best for you. I=
f your nose is higher on your face, you may want a frame style where the br=
idge is even with the brow line. If your nose is positioned lower on your f=
ace, consider frames with a lower bridge and curved brow line.</p>
                                    <div class=3D"light-icon-content">
                                        <div class=3D"light-icon-desc selec=
ting-icon-desc">
                                            <ins class=3D"im"></ins>
                                            <span>To get your bridge measur=
ement, find the distance between the inner edges of each lens.</span>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <!-- Find the Perfect Frames for You -->
